Then I created the sorted file named "words" in my working directory.
$ sort /usr/share/dict/words > words

Then I created the text file containing the HTML in this assignment's web page.
$ wget http://web.cs.ucla.edu/classes/fall17/cs35L/assign/assign2.html

Run the commands with the HTML assign2.html file being standard input:
(In order to observe the output, I put the output into a file named test.txt)

Before running the commands, I firstly read the man page of tr.
I know that -c means complement and -s means squeeze-repeats.

$ tr -c 'A-Za-z' '[\n*]' <assign2.html > test.txt

This command change all the characters other than 'A-Za-z' into a newline.
Notice that the space before the public is TAB, which counts as one character.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

$ tr -cs 'A-Za-z' '[\n*]' < assign2.html >test.txt

This command squeeze the mutiple new lines into just one new lines.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Before running the command, I read the man page of sort, which sort lines of 
text files.

$ tr -cs 'A-Za-z' '[\n*]'< assign2.html | sort

